<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-717-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 717 724.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  July 30 1990 n379 p67(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GUIs should help users, not MIS, be more efficient. (graphicaluser interface) (Soft Focus) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rose, Philip F.H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The current contention of graphical user interface advocates thatan interface should be consistent across an operating system losessight of the real purpose of a GUI.andP;  A GUI provides a user with aconsistent and appropriate interface while insuring that systemscan share messages and data across a network and that theinterfaces are relatively intuitive.andP;  The reduced training,technical support and maintenance costs for MIS offered by a GUIare not as important as the gains of the individual user, who willalso generate savings by needing less training for new software onthe same system.andP;  The market will eventually come to realize thatthe benefits of having people use the most appropriate environmentfor a given task outweigh the increased training and supportcosts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceAnalysisCritiquePerformance ImprovementMISUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>